{
    "analysis": "The Executor returned a compact summary of all four telemetry files: metric, trace, log, and error_logs. We have time coverage for the incident window (2022-03-21 00:00 to 00:29 UTC+8) and many candidate components (top aggregated cmdb_ids include adservice, frontend pods, checkoutservice pods, etc.). The metric file contains many container- and node-level KPIs with sufficient samples. According to the diagnosis workflow, the next step is to calculate global thresholds for each component-KPI (using the entire available series for that component-KPI) and then detect anomalies inside the incident window to narrow down faulty components and KPIs. We must therefore compute per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) global P95 and P5 from the full metric.csv, then inspect the incident window for high or low anomalies, returning compact ranked candidates (bounded output) that show the most anomaly occurrences and earliest anomaly timestamp. This will allow us to prioritize which components/KPIs to inspect further via traces and logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, do the following (keep outputs compact and bounded):\n1) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present in metric.csv, compute global P95 and P5 using the entire available time series in the file (do NOT pre-filter by time). Also compute the full-series count of points for that pair.\n2) Filter metric.csv to the incident window of March 21, 2022 00:00 to 00:30 (UTC+8) and for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: total_points_in_window, count_points_ge_P95 (value >= P95), earliest_timestamp_ge_P95 (first timestamp in window where value >= P95, or null), count_points_le_P5 (value <= P5), earliest_timestamp_le_P5 (first timestamp in window where value <= P5, or null), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window.\n3) Return a single compact table limited to the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs ranked by max(count_points_ge_P95, count_points_le_P5) in descending order. Include these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, full_series_count, P95, P5, total_points_in_window, count_points_ge_P95, earliest_timestamp_ge_P95, count_points_le_P5, earliest_timestamp_le_P5, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window.\n4) If fewer than 20 pairs have any anomalies in the window, return only those with anomalies. Keep the result bounded to at most 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step (metric analysis) scanned metric.csv and computed global thresholds (P95/P5) per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full series, then inspected the incident window 2022-03-21 00:00–00:30 (UTC+8). The top anomalous pairs returned were all constant-value series for shippingservice2-0 tied to many container.node-5.* KPIs; these are not informative because P95==P5==observed value, so they appear as 'anomalous' but show no spikes or drops. We need to pivot to traces to find functional anomalies and to localize which service/pod is failing during the two failures in the given window. Trace analysis can identify downstream failing services or high latency/error spikes that metrics missed.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv only, do the following (keep outputs compact and bounded):\n1) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in trace.csv, compute global P95 and P5 using the entire available series in the file (do NOT pre-filter by time). Also return the full-series count.\n2) Filter trace.csv to the incident window March 21, 2022 00:00 to 00:30 (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: total_points_in_window, count_points_ge_P95 (value >= P95), earliest_timestamp_ge_P95 (first timestamp in window where value >= P95 or null), count_points_le_P5 (value <= P5), earliest_timestamp_le_P5 (first timestamp in window where value <= P5 or null), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window.\n3) Return a compact table limited to the top 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs ranked by max(count_points_ge_P95, count_points_le_P5) in descending order. Include columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, full_series_count, P95, P5, total_points_in_window, count_points_ge_P95, earliest_timestamp_ge_P95, count_points_le_P5, earliest_timestamp_le_P5, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window.\n4) If fewer than 20 pairs show any anomalies, return only those with anomalies. Limit rows to at most 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis (previous step) computed global P95/P5 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) and inspected the incident window; results show many trace error_rate and other trace series are constant (P95==P5==0) across the full series and the window, so no clear anomalies were found via traces. Metric analysis earlier also returned mostly constant series flagged by equal P95/P5, which are not informative. Since metrics and traces did not surface time-localized spikes/drops, the next logical step is focused log analysis: error logs often contain explicit error messages and timestamps that reveal failure occurrences, and aggregated log.error_count can show which components experienced increased error counts during the two failures. We should compute global thresholds for log KPIs, then inspect the incident window to find components with elevated log.error_count or many error log messages. This will narrow candidate components and exact failure timestamps for root-cause localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze log.csv and error_logs.csv (keep outputs compact):\n1) From log.csv: For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute full-series P95 and P5 and full_series_count (use entire file). Then filter to the incident window March 21, 2022 00:00 to 00:30 (UTC+8) and for each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute: total_points_in_window, sum_value_in_window, count_values_gt_P95 (value > P95), earliest_timestamp_value_gt_P95 (first timestamp in window where value > P95 or null), count_values_lt_P5 (value < P5), earliest_timestamp_value_lt_P5 (first timestamp in window where value < P5 or null). Return the top 20 (cmdb_id, log_name) pairs ranked by sum_value_in_window (descending). Include columns: cmdb_id, log_name, full_series_count, P95, P5, total_points_in_window, sum_value_in_window, count_values_gt_P95, earliest_timestamp_value_gt_P95, count_values_lt_P5, earliest_timestamp_value_lt_P5.\n2) From error_logs.csv: Filter rows to the incident window March 21, 2022 00:00 to 00:30 (UTC+8). Return a compact summary: total_rows_in_window, unique_cmdb_count_in_window, and a table of top 10 cmdb_id by count of error log rows in-window with columns: cmdb_id, count_in_window, earliest_timestamp_in_window, latest_timestamp_in_window. Also for the top 3 cmdb_id by count, return up to 20 unique message samples (message text) and their individual counts, limited to top 20 messages per component.\nLimit all returned lists/tables to the requested maxima to keep outputs bounded."
}

{
    "analysis": "From previous steps: metric and trace data show mostly constant series and did not localize time-localized metric anomalies. Log-level aggregates (log.row_count) show brief 1–2 minute spikes/dips across many services. error_logs.csv shows concentrated error messages on frontend-0, frontend-2, and frontend-1 with hundreds of error rows across the whole 00:00–00:30 window, dominated by a single repeated warning message per frontend. This strongly indicates the frontends were experiencing errors during the window. To identify the two distinct failures (their exact occurrence times and root cause components), we need per-minute event-level aggregation: find minutes when many services simultaneously had log.row_count > their global P95 and find minutes with peaks in error_log row counts. Comparing these will let us identify the two failure timestamps and confirm the root component(s).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Aggregate log.csv and error_logs.csv within the incident window (2022-03-21 00:00–00:30 UTC+8) and return compact ranked tables (no raw full tables):\n1) From log.csv: for each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute global P95 using full series (entire file). Then, for every minute in the incident window, compute: timestamp (minute), number_of_components_where_log.row_count > that component's P95, list_of_up_to_20_cmdb_ids_exceeding_P95 (limit 20), and sum_log_row_count_across_all_components for that minute. Return the top 10 minutes ranked by number_of_components_where_log.row_count > P95 (desc); include the listed columns. If ties, secondary sort by sum_log_row_count desc.\n2) From error_logs.csv: aggregate to per-minute counts within the window. Return the top 10 minutes ranked by total_error_log_rows (desc) with columns: timestamp (minute), total_error_rows, top_5_cmdb_ids_with_counts_for_that_minute (cmdb_id:count pairs), earliest_error_timestamp_in_minute (smallest timestamp in that minute), latest_error_timestamp_in_minute (largest timestamp in that minute).\n3) Additionally, return the earliest two distinct minutes that appear as peaks in both tables (i.e., minutes present among the top 10 in both aggregations). If none overlap, return the top two minutes from the error_logs table.\nKeep all outputs compact and bounded as requested (lists limited to 20 or 5 entries where specified)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through preprocessing, metric scanning, trace scanning, and log analysis. Findings so far: (1) metric series were mostly constant and not useful for anomaly spikes; (2) trace counts show frontends issued many requests at early minutes (00:00, 00:02) and again at 00:15; (3) error_logs are heavily concentrated on frontend-0/1/2 with repeated identical warning messages \"failed to retrieve...\" at the two candidate minutes (00:00 and 00:02 UTC+8), each minute showing 23 error rows across the three frontends; (4) trace duration metrics at 00:02 show a larger value (max ~0.0835s) for frontend-2→checkoutservice, but overall durations are small (fractions of a second). From the workflow: we must now determine whether frontends themselves are failing (container or process or network issues) or they are experiencing failures due to downstream services (e.g., productcatalogservice or currencyservice) or network. To decide, we need to inspect trace error_rate/duration for the suspected downstream services at those same minutes to see if they themselves show elevated error_rate or latency that would explain frontend \"failed to retrieve\" warnings. This step is necessary before concluding root cause component and reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter trace.csv to timestamps exactly 2022-03-21 00:00:00+08:00 and 2022-03-21 00:02:00+08:00. Select rows where cmdb_id starts with \"productcatalogservice\" OR starts with \"currencyservice\" OR starts with \"checkoutservice\" OR cmdb_id in [\"frontend-0\",\"frontend-1\",\"frontend-2\"]. From those rows, keep trace_name entries that contain any of: \"error_rate\", \"duration\", \"duration_mean\", \"duration_p95\", \"duration_p50\". Return a single compact table limited to the top 50 rows ranked by value descending with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value. If fewer than 50 rows match, return them all. Keep output bounded."
}

